Comment in
    JAMA. 1991 Mar 6;265(9):1111-2.

To assess excess mortality from chronic disease in the United States, state 
age-adjusted combined mortality rates for nine chronic diseases in 1986 were 
compared with three "minimum" rates--two calculated from rates actually achieved 
in states and a third estimated as the mortality remaining after elimination of 
one risk factor for each disease. Hawaii had the lowest mortality rate of 
combined diseases (305/100,000); state excesses ranged from 0% to 37%. The sum 
